    {
      "id": "passage_1",
      "text": "The term Anthropocene characterizes a new geological epoch (1)____ by the significant impact of human activities on Earth's ecosystems. While the exact starting point remains a matter of (2)____ among scientists, most agree that the mid-20th century (3)____ a profound shift. This period, often called the 'Great Acceleration,' saw (4)____ increases in population, carbon emissions, and plastic production. Consequently, the planetary boundaries that once (5)____ stability are now being pushed to their limits. (6)____, the loss of biodiversity has reached levels not seen since the last mass extinction. Critics of the term argue that it (7)____ the responsibility of a few industrialized nations onto humanity as a whole. (8)____, the geological evidence of human influence—from radioactive isotopes to nitrogen (9)____—is undeniable. In order to (10)____ these global challenges, a multidisciplinary approach is required. Scholars (11)____ that unless we transition to sustainable energy sources, the (12)____ effects on the climate will be irreversible. This transition (13)____ not only technological innovation but also a fundamental (14)____ in how societies value natural resources. The (15)____ of our actions today will define the geological record for millions of years to come."
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_2",
      "text": "Artificial Intelligence (AI) has undergone a (16)____ transformation since its inception in the 1950s. Initially, researchers (17)____ on symbolic AI, which relied on hard-coded rules. However, this approach (18)____ to be insufficient for complex tasks like image recognition. The (19)____ of machine learning shifted the focus toward algorithms that could learn from data. By (20)____ vast amounts of information, these systems can now (21)____ patterns that were previously invisible to human analysts. (22)____, the rise of deep learning, inspired by the structure of the human brain, has further (23)____ the field. Despite these advancements, ethical (24)____ remain a primary concern. There is a fear that biased data could (25)____ existing social inequalities. Furthermore, the (26)____ nature of 'black box' algorithms makes it difficult to understand how certain decisions are (27)____. To mitigate these risks, many organizations are (28)____ for 'Explainable AI'. This movement (29)____ to make the decision-making process more transparent. Ultimately, the goal is to create systems that (30)____ human intelligence rather than replace it."
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_3",
      "text": "Understanding how students (31)____ knowledge is central to educational psychology. For decades, the behaviorist perspective (32)____ that learning was primarily a response to external stimuli. In (33)____, the constructivist theory suggests that learners (34)____ build their own understanding based on prior experiences. This shift has led to more (35)____ learning environments where students are encouraged to explore. One (36)____ factor in successful learning is metacognition, or the ability to (37)____ one's own thought processes. Students who possess high metacognitive skills are better at (38)____ goals and monitoring their progress. (39)____, motivation plays a (40)____ role in academic achievement. Intrinsic motivation, which (41)____ from an internal desire to learn, is generally more sustainable than extrinsic motivation. However, the (42)____ of modern classrooms often makes it difficult to foster such engagement. Teachers must (43)____ various instructional strategies to cater to diverse learning styles. (44)____, the use of technology in the classroom has (45)____ both opportunities and challenges. While digital tools can (46)____ collaboration, they can also serve as (47)____ if not managed properly. Research (48)____ that a balanced approach, combining traditional methods with digital (49)____, yields the best results. Educators must remain (50)____ to new findings in the field to optimize student outcomes."
    }
  ],
